<h1>Marathons are for the insane. And you want to become certified insane!</h1>

<p>
    In order to run a marathon, we often think that we have to undergo drastic changes in our life.  This is not true.
    Most successful runners have balanced lives with families, forty-hour work weeks, and many other responsibilities. 
    In my case, I found out that running itself is what helped me manage the other aspects of my life that I thought were
    out of my control, such as personal finance, my career as a software developer, and enterprenuer, by learning how 
    to systematically change a small habits in my daily life. I have come up with a list of things that will help you 
    become a successful runner and a healthier and happier human being.
</p>
<h3>
    1) You'll need a plan. 
</h3>
<p>
    Whether you want to complete a marathon, or qualify for Boston, you will want a plan. 
    Not just any plan, you will want a plan for you, and that details your day-to-day activities. You'll want this because
    it takes out the calculations and stipulations. The plan you need will provide you with a list of steps, broken down into 
    digestable and purposeful runs.
</p>
<h3>
    2) Strava or Garmin
</h3>
<p>
    Strava and Garmin are apps that help you log your training. Keeping track of your training is important because it does 
    two things.  First, it keeps you in check. I'm not a person that needs to be in check, right? Wrong. It helps you from over training, 
    and cooling your jets, to the opposite end of the spectrum of keeping you accountable.
    Secondly, it is an investment in your future. Strava, and Garmin, help you visualize your progress. Visualizing your
    training helps you see patterns for those hamstrings strains, unexpected fatigue, and personal bests. 
    Data is a secret to your success! (If you are the bohemian nomad, who's proud to be off grid, a training diary that logs you feeling of
    effort and time run can be a powerful substitution for the kudos hungry Stravians.)
</p>
<h3>
    3) Starting slow, and staying consistent
</h3>
<p>
    Marathons are hard. They are like no other race. It is not like a walk in the park, or neighboorhood 5K, or even it's evil younger brother
    the half marathon.  It is an entirely different Event.  Captial E because it is the thing that requires you to stick to your plan and respect.
    Your pursuit in this can be simplified by starting slow and staying consistent. Over time, you will learn how to acknowledge yourself 
    and where you stand. 
</p>

